==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: wick
<hw>wick</hw> <pr>(w⟦icr⟧k)</pr>, <it>or</it>

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: wick
<hw>wick</hw> <pr>(w⟦icr⟧k)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>wicke</ets>, <ets>weyke</ets>, <ets>weke</ets>, AS.
<ets>weoca</ets> or <ets>wecca</ets>; cf. D. <ets>wiek</ets> a roll of
lint, Prov. G. <ets>wicke</ets>, and <ets>wieche</ets>, OHG.
<ets>wiohha</ets>, Sw. <ets>veke</ets>, Dan. <ets>v⟦ae⟧ge</ets>; of
uncertain origin.]</ety> <def>A bundle of fibers, or a loosely twisted
or braided cord, tape, or tube, usually made of soft spun cotton
threads, which by capillary attraction draws up a steady supply of the
oil in lamps, the melted tallow or wax in candles, or other material
used for illumination, in small successive portions, to be
burned.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But true it is, that when the oil is spent⟦br⟧
The light goes out, and <qex>wick</qex> is thrown away.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>wick</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: wick
<hw>wick</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <fld>(Curling)</fld> <def>To strike a
stone in an oblique direction.</def> <rj><au>Jamieson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>wicke</ent>⟦br⟧
